Happy Friday, We have sent out Superintendent Kubin‚Äôs parent communication to parents and guardians with information about Tutors, After School Extra-Curricular Groups, and Support available for your children. Thank you for all of the fantastic feedback you have given everyone throughout our District. We have made notable progress over the first few weeks of school, but we are never done learning and improving what we do so please continue to give us feedback on what is working and what you may need.

UUSD Food Distribution Tomorrow, Wednesday, Sept. 2, 2020
Food will be provided for UUSD Students at one location, Ukiah High School, from 6:30 a.m. to 6:30 p.m., every Wednesday. Food distribution will happen regardless of the weather. No bus deliveries. We must be able to put food in the trunk or back of your SUV or truck; we can no longer put food in front or back seats.

This year, we are excited to offer free breakfast and lunch to every Ukiah Unified student, thanks to a California program. We hope you take advantage of this program so that every student can access healthy, nutritious meals.

We hope to have Fuji apples and potatoes in tomorrow‚Äôs distribution. Come early; some food items are limited. Remember to wear a mask and practice physical distancing when picking up food. Please reach out to your school for support or call 707.472.5003. And don‚Äôt forget to read with your kids!

Thank you to everyone in our community for your incredible hard work and patience as we begin the 2020-2021 school year. Our goal is to provide the best Distance Learning experience possible, and we are committed to the social-emotional health of our students. https://www.uusd.net/apps/news/article/1285039

We want to partner with parents and guardians to make sure kids feel supported, and everyone has access to the resources they need during these challenging times. Please reach out to your child‚Äôs school or email the school counselor for help or support. You can find the contact information for counselors, schools, and mental health resources here: https://www.uusd.net/apps/pages/mentalhealth.

Thank you for supporting the children in our community with your kindness, flexibility, and positivity! Please let us know what you need! Reach out to your school for more information; they are very busy, so be sure to leave a message or call our District Hotline at 707-472-5003.

Food will be provided for UUSD STUDENTS ONLY at one location, Ukiah High School, from 6:30 a.m. to 6:30 p.m., every Wednesday. Food distribution will happen regardless of the weather. No bus deliveries. We must be able to put food in the trunk or back of your SUV or truck; we can no longer put food in front or back seats.

Parents and guardians who receive meals need to provide their child‚Äôs student ID number. If you do not know your child‚Äôs student ID number, you can find it on the Aeries Parent Portal. Call your school for assistance. We hope to have chicken, pork, cheese, tangerines, cantaloupe and honeydew melons, yams, cauliflower, juice, chocolate milk, and popsicles in tomorrow‚Äôs distribution.

We hope you‚Äôre having a fantastic first week of school. Please reach out to your school for assistance or call 707.472.5003.

post_text:
UUSD was notified today that an employee has tested positive for COVID-19. Out of an abundance of caution, we canceled UHS Chromebook distribution for the rest of today and tomorrow. The health and safety of our students and staff is a priority. We have contacted Public Health to ensure we are taking all of the steps necessary to keep our students and staff safe in this situation.

It is unlikely that there would be any exposure due to having picked up a Chromebook; however, if you have already picked up your Chromebook this morning, please let the Chromebook sit for 72 hours and disinfect the Chromebook with disinfecting wipes.

Ukiah Unified will be doing additional disinfecting of Chromebooks before any further distribution this week and next week. Chromebook distribution will begin again on Thursday, August 13, 2020. A detailed revised schedule will be distributed tomorrow afternoon.

Food will be provided for any child 18 years or younger every Wednesday at one location, Ukiah High School, from 7:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. Children do not need to be present.

Next week, Wednesday, August 12, 2020, will be the last Summer Food Distribution. Please remember to wear a mask and practice physical distancing when picking up food. We hope you are having a fantastic summer, please stay safe and healthy and remember, READ to your kids!

post_text:
Ukiah High School is offering our annual Summer Academy Program in virtual form for the incoming 9th-grade class. Thank you for those who applied to our Summer Academy program, we appreciate your interest and efforts. We look forward to meeting each of you and sharing your high school experience with you. Through our teachers, leadership students, and staff, we have created a virtual experience for the entire UHS Class of 2024 to learn as much as possible about Ukiah High School.

We will take you on a virtual tour of our campus, introduce you to staff and students and your academic counselor, and share the variety of classes, programs, sports, clubs, pathways, and adventures available over the next four years. Beginning Monday, July 27, we will share a daily video, each with a new focus or theme via your student email and our UHS website. The in-depth and detailed orientation will familiarize you with what it means to be a member of the Ukiah High School Wildcat Nation. Welcome, Class of 2024!

Summer Food Distribution will take place tomorrow, Wednesday, July 1, 2020. Food for 15 meals will be provided for any child 18 years or younger every Wednesday at one location, Ukiah High School, from 7:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. Food deliveries by bus will not take place over the Summer.

Farmers to Families Food Box
The USDA is partnering with farmers, ranchers, food processors, distributors, and non-profits to ensure that all Americans have access to the food they need during the COVID-19 national emergency. Thanks to this program, in addition to our regular food distribution items, families will be able to pick up a Farmers to Families Food Box tomorrow with 20 pounds of pork, and 20 pounds of cheese.

Please remember to wear a mask and practice social distancing when picking up food.

Call us at 707-472-5003 with questions. We hope you are having a fantastic summer, please stay safe and healthy and remember to READ with your kids!

Big Picture Ukiah staff greeting students yesterday.

South Valley High School students are involved in a ground-breaking alternative education program called Big Picture Ukiah. This is a student-centered learning system, where students pursue their interests with a community of educators, local professionals, family members, and fellow students. Each student is urged and supported to complete a local internship working closely with a local mentor, learning in the real world. Thank you, Big Picture Ukiah staff, for everything you do!

post_text:
Due to Coronavirus (COVID-19), children who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals at school will get extra food benefits. These food benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT benefits. P-EBT benefits help families in California buy food when schools are closed because of the coronavirus emergency.

Families will get up to $365 per eligible child on their P-EBT card to use on food and groceries.

Families with children who get CalFresh, Medi-Cal or Foster Care benefits do not need to apply. Most will get their P-EBT card in the mail during the month of May. P-EBT cards will begin arriving around May 12, 2020. Others may apply here starting May 22nd: https://ca.p-ebt.org/

The Mendocino County Office of Education has partnered with the Ukiah Daily Journal to create a special magazine to help celebrate the graduating classes of 2020. This special insert will be published on Friday, June 12, 2020, and will feature a listing of all Mendocino County high school graduates.

Parents, Friends, and Relatives will have the opportunity to put a business card size ad in the magazine for just $25 with the help of business sponsors in our community. These ads can include 1 photo (we are encouraging baby photos!) and up to 50 words.

Please contact Molly Lane at advertising@record-bee.com or (707) 263-5636 to purchase an ad to congratulate your favorite graduate!

Business owners and community members can send a message to the 2020 Graduates of Mendocino County by purchasing full-color ads. Please contact Sarah McGrath at smcgrath@record-bee.com. The deadline is Friday, May 15, 2020. https://www.uusd.net/apps/news/article/1227997

post_text:
Eagle Peak Middle School student A.J. Bass has won the Grand Prize in the nationally acclaimed Jostens 2020 Photo Contest. Bass, a 7th grader, and first-year digital media student, was honored for his photo, ON THE MAT! Bass will receive a cash prize along with a camera equipment package and will be featured in several Jostens publications.

Nearly 5,000 photo entries were received from middle and high school student photographers across the country. From these entries, only 108 photos were selected as the award winners, and Bass‚Äô photo claimed the overall Grand Prize.

Three other students from Eagle Peak were also recognized for their photographs. Beyanah Boek took 5th place in the Photo Illustration/Manipulation category for the photo, MAGICAL MOTHER EARTH. Davin Friedland earned an Honorable Mention in the Portrait category for the photo, BEHIND THE GLOVE, and Dakota Hill received an Honorable Mention for the photo, NOSE GOES, in the Middle School category.

Weekly Superintendent‚Äôs Update to Ukiah Unified Families April 10, 2020

We have emailed a communication to parents with the details about meal pickups and delivery, as well as important information about Social-Emotional Health and Remote Learning. You can also find the communication at www.uusd.net.

We will be serving meals once next week on Tuesday, April 14, 2020, from 11:00 a.m. - 1:00 p.m. at six Ukiah Unified schools including Ukiah High School, Oak Manor, Eagle Peak, Grace Hudson, Yokayo, and Pomolita. Meals will also be delivered by bus. Please visit www.uusd.net and click on the link next to the yellow school bus to see delivery times and places.

It is important to know that we now require those who receive meals to have proof that their child resides in our community such as a report card, student ID, letter, or email from a school. If children are present, no proof is needed.

Beginning on Monday, April 20, 2020, meals will be served only one time each week on Mondays and will contain five days of meals.

Thank you so much for your continued support.

During stressful times, it is essential to stay calm, listen, and offer reassurance to our children. Follow this link to read Superintendent Kubin‚Äôs blog about children and COVID-19. https://www.uusd.net/apps/news/article/1207898

If your child is having difficulty dealing with this or any stressful situation, don‚Äôt feel alone. Do not hesitate to reach out for help. For children in our Ukiah Unified schools, you can call your child‚Äôs school or e-mail the school counselors for support. Because it is more challenging to communicate during this remote learning period, if you are unable to reach your child‚Äôs school, you can call UUSD‚Äôs Remote Learning Hotline at 707-472-5003.
Additionally, the County of Mendocino has the Warm Line for community members to call for non-crisis, emotional support at 707-472-2311. And finally, in a crisis, please call the Mendocino County Crisis Hotline at 855-838-0404, 24 hours a day, seven days a week.

When you hear, read, or watch news about an outbreak of infectious disease, you may feel anxious and show signs of stress. These signs of stress are normal and may be more likely in people with loved ones in parts of the world affected by the outbreak.

During an infectious disease outbreak, care for your own physical and mental health and reach out with kindness to those affected by the situation.

Starting tomorrow, Friday, March 20, 2020, we will start delivering meals by bus for all students and any child 18 years of age or younger in our district. We will have five routes providing meals to children in our district running from Monday through Friday until further notice. Please visit www.uusd.net and click on the link next to the bright yellow school bus to see a list of food delivery stops and times.

Meal pickups at school sites will also continue. Stop in and pick up meals from 11:00 a.m. ‚Äì 1:00 p.m., Monday through Friday at Frank Zeek, Grace Hudson, Nokomis, Oak Manor, and Yokayo Elementary Schools. In the Hopland, Calpella, and Eagle Peak areas, the schools are one of the stops on the bus route. Students must be present due to state requirements.

If you have questions about the bus schedule, call 707-472-5090.

post_text:
Due to increased concerns about the COVID-19 situation and the potential impact on our schools and community, it is with a heavy heart that we announce we will be suspending site-based instruction at all Ukiah Unified School District schools beginning Tuesday, March 17th through Spring Break on Monday, April 13th. We are holding classes tomorrow so that students are able to pick up instructional materials.
We will be transitioning all students to remote learning, which means that students do not physically attend school, but receive and complete lessons at home.
All after school activities, child care, and field trips will be canceled during this time as well. Prior to April 13, we will evaluate the situation and make a determination if we are able to resume site-based instruction.
We will be communicating more in the near future about remote learning, meals, and social-emotional support for our students. You may also check www.uusd.net to find out more.

To encourage more families to take advantage of the healthy choices available for school breakfast, Ukiah Unified School District will celebrate National School Breakfast Week during March 2-6, 2020.

Don‚Äôt forget all meals are free for all students all the time! UUSD Food Service prepares meals every day that meet federal nutrition standards ‚Äì limiting fat, calories, and sodium ‚Äì while encouraging students to choose from the fruits, vegetables, and whole grains offered. Check out your school‚Äôs website for their menu.

When students eat a nutritious school breakfast they are more likely to:
‚Ä¢ Reach higher levels of achievement in reading and math
‚Ä¢ Score higher on standardized tests
‚Ä¢ Have better concentration and memory
‚Ä¢ Be more alert
‚Ä¢ Maintain a healthy weight

text: Due to law enforcement activity in the area, UHS, Pomolita, and Frank Zeek schools were briefly put on lockdown. That lockdown has now been lifted. The activity was not related to school or our campuses in any way.

post_text:
UPDATE: the lockdown has been lifted. We have been working closely with law enforcement and it is now safe to lift the lockdown.

There is a shelter in place at UHS, Pomolita, and Frank Zeek due to law enforcement activity in the area. It is not related to school or our campuses in any way. Out of an abundance of precaution, we have locked down the three schools.
text:
UPDATE: the lockdown has been lifted. We have been working closely with law enforcement and it is now safe to lift the lockdown.

There is a shelter in place at UHS, Pomolita, and Frank Zeek due to law enforcement activity in the area. It is not related to school or our campuses in any way. Out of an abundance of precaution, we have locked down the three schools.

post_text: January 2020 UUSD Students of the Month!
text: January 2020 UUSD Students of the Month!

post_text:
Yokayo Elementary participated in The Great Kindness Challenge last week. This challenge is a celebration where students do as many acts of kindness as possible. Organized by Kids for Peace in 2012, the Great Kindness Challenge has now grown to over 15 million students in all 50 states.

In addition to all students receiving a 50-item act of kindness checklist, classrooms hosted kindness activities throughout the week. Yokayo provided kindness recess stations, school-wide service projects, and a variety of community kindness outreach opportunities for students. Teachers provided kindness-based lesson plans, students learned famous quotes about kindness, and they had kindness-based spirit days. Students provided kindness! www.kidsforpeaceglobal.org

Watch as Ukiah High School Automotive students change brake calipers on a 2003 Nissan Sentra!

Ukiah High School offers 16 different Career Technical Education (CTE) Pathways that prepare students for a career in a related field. CTE Pathways include Automotive Technology, Animal Science, Automotive Mechanics, Child Development, Computer-Aided Drafting (CAD), Computer Science, Construction Trades, Digital Media, Fashion, Health Occupations, Horticulture, Machine Shop, Photography, Sustainable Agriculture, Welding, and Residential and Commercial Construction. To find out more about Ukiah High School‚Äôs CTE Programs or to become involved in an Advisory Council, contact Eric Crawford, CTE Coordinator, at 707.472.5875 or ecrawford@uusd.net.

National School Counseling Week highlights the unique contribution of school counselors within our school system and the tremendous impact they have on helping students achieve educational success and plan for a career. Visit www.schoolcounselor.org for more information, and please thank our school counselors for everything they do for our children.

post_text:
UUSD Eighth-graders at Ukiah High School
Eighth-grade middle school students are visiting Ukiah High School this week as part of their high school transition process. Students get a tour of the campus led by UHS Link Crew members, and they learn all about electives and Career Technical Education (CTE) pathways. Middle School counselors have also started working with our 8th-grade students to prepare them for the transition to high school. Students are receiving presentations about high school graduation requirements, A-G college admissions requirements, and CTE pathways.

post_text:
Eagle Peak Middle School hosted the G-4 Science Summit Night on January 23, 2020, celebrating students engaged in science. Students prepare projects with an area of focus for each grade level including Food and Agriculture, Energy, Air and Space, and Water. Students are encouraged to choose a project that can help with a real-world problem. Ambassadors are chosen from each grade to create action plans to implement and follow up on top projects. In addition to all of the student projects on display, there were activity tables for kids to engage in science activities.

2020 Ambassadors:
5th: Skylyn Glassey
6th: Amy Hernandez
7th: Jade L'Heureux
8th: Austin Pardini and Carson Galetti

Photos courtesy of Bailey Harris, Eagle Peak Middle School 8th-Grader.

Ukiah High School Intro to Drama Class and EL Students

The Ukiah High School Freshmen Introduction to Drama class with teacher Maria Monti and the English Language Development class with teacher Corina Edwards combined their classes several years ago. The EL students learn English faster when working with the Drama students, and the Drama students learn by clearly communicating and speaking with EL students, and they can practice their Spanish too.

post_text:
CO2 Dragster Racing at Eagle Peak Middle School
This is a great STEM activity where students design and build an actual CO2-powered dragster and then race it against their classmates! Thank you Eagle Peak Teacher, Chris Percy, for this great learning activity! CO2 dragsters are miniature racing cars that are propelled by a carbon dioxide cartridge that is pierced to start the release of the gas. The car is made from balsa wood and utilizes two hooks (eyelets or screw eyes) linked to a string on the bottom of the car to prevent the vehicle from losing control during a launch. The cars race on a 60-foot track and help teach students about mechanical principles such as mass, force, acceleration, drag, wind resistance, and aerodynamics. This year‚Äôs winner is Willem Brower!

shared_text:

shared_text:
City of Ukiah Police Department is at Walmart Ukiah.
November 5, 2019 at 3:52 PM ¬∑ Ukiah, CA ¬∑

We are excited to announce that we have been awarded a $2000 grant from Walmart Giving to support our Gang Resistance Education And Training (G.R.E.A.T.) Program.

G.R.E.A.T. is a 13-lesson middle school curriculum and 6-lesson elementary school curriculum which is designed as an immunization against delinquency, youth violence, and gang membership for children in the years immediately before the prime ages for introduction into gangs and delinquent behavior.

The funds from this grant will be utilized to supply our G.R.E.A.T. students with graduation parties to celebrate their completion of this structured program.

With sponsors such as Walmart, we can make an impact in our community together.

post_text:
Student and staff safety is a priority at Ukiah Unified. Shortly after school started today, the smell of gas was noticed around Yokayo Elementary School. To ensure student safety, students were evacuated to the athletic field. Out of an abundance of caution for student safety, Ukiah Unified determined it was necessary to close Yokayo Elementary School until the source of the gas smell was located.

The source of that smell was determined to be a failed pilot light and is currently being repaired. The safety system functioned properly and the gas was automatically turned off. Students and staff were safe at all times.

We are grateful to Ukiah Police Department, Ukiah Valley Fire Authority, P.G.&E. and our wonderful staff for their work to keep our students, staff, and families safe and calm during an emergency.
--

Thank You, School Administrators!
October 13th through the 19th is Week of the School Administrator in observance of the importance of educational leadership at our schools, school districts, and county offices of education. Let‚Äôs join together and thank school administrators for the contributions they make to successful student achievement every day.

School administrators are passionate, lifelong educators who believe in the value of quality public education. Superintendents, assistant superintendents, principals, assistant principals, special education and adult education leaders, curriculum and assessment leaders, school business officials, classified educational leaders, and many other school district employees are all considered school administrators. California school administrators serve over 6 million students!
